> If you want to eat your dessert straight after your main, do steps 7 and 8
> (the crumble prep) before you start preparing the main. Pop the crumble into
> your oven (step 9) once you've finished cooking and are plating up your main.

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450}(chopped into 2cm chunks, no
need to peel) into chunks. Pop the chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle
with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in
a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and
chopped into small pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and
grated) or use a #garlic press{}. Halve the @lemon{1/2}(halved, zest it first if
you haven't already for the dessert). Finely chop the @chives{1}(finely chopped).
Trim the bottom 2cm from the @asparagus{200%g} and discard.

Lay the @sea bream fillets{2}, skin-side up, onto a baking tray lined with
#baking paper{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Once the potatoes have been
cooking for ~{15%minutes}, bake the fish on the middle shelf until cooked,
~{10-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish. The fish
> is cooked when opaque in the middle.

While the fish bakes, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat. Once hot, add the shallot and cook until softened,
~{3-4%minutes}. Add the garlic and stir-fry, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in the
@water{50%ml} for the sauce, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @Dijon mustard{10%g}
and two thirds of the @creme fraiche{150%g} (set the rest aside for the dessert).
Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened,
~{3-4%minutes}. Remove from the heat. Squeeze in some lemon juice to taste, and
stir through half the chives.

While the sauce simmers, bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{} to the boil with
@salt{1/4%tsp} for the asparagus. Just before you are ready to serve, add the
asparagus to the boiling water and cook until tender, ~{1-2%minutes}. Drain well
in a #colander{}, then pop back into the pan. Drizzle with a little @oil{} and
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

When everything is ready, transfer the sea bream to your plates. Warm through
the sauce if needed.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if it's a little thick.

Spoon the creamy sauce over the bream, then sprinkle over the remaining chives.
Enjoy!

== Apple Crumble Dessert ==

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Peel, quarter, core and roughly chop your
@apple{4}(peeled, quartered and roughly chopped). Zest and halve the
@lemon{1/2}(zested and halved). Reserve 1/2 tbsp of the @caster sugar{75%g} per
person and set aside for sprinkling over the crumble later. Pop the apples into
a #medium bowl{} with the lemon zest and half the remaining sugar. Mix to coat
the apples well, then set aside.

Chop the @unsalted butter{60%g} into 1cm pieces. In a large #bowl{}, combine the
@plain flour{75%g} and the remaining sugar, then add the chopped butter and rub
in with your fingertips until it resembles breadcrumbs. Spoon the apple mixture
into an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{} and top with an even layer of
crumble mixture. Sprinkle the reserved sugar over the top.

When ready, bake the crumble on the top shelf of your oven until the top is
golden and the apple is bubbling, ~{35-40%minutes}. Once baked, remove from the
oven and allow to cool slightly before serving. Serve in bowls with the
remaining creme fraiche spooned over. Enjoy!